    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9c7dca55_22a7ae5a",
        "filename": "android/base/network/IpAddress.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 47,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-10-14T14:17:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "|string[string.size()]| is technically out-of-bounds access for a StringView, so no :-/\n\nThere is no way to safely do what you want here. The alternative is to change the constructor to take a |const char *| instead, to be passed directly to inet_pton(AF_INET,...)",
      "parentUuid": "df9654c8_56971449",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 47,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 47,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "39856ce8646c65ac26e12030542d35508ac972cd",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3cf3ffac_e9eb6e35",
        "filename": "android/base/network/IpAddress.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 47,
      "author": {
        "id": 1080076
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-10-18T20:31:03Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I will add a comment and assert to StringView to make sure it\u0027s end() is dereferencable. The only case when it isn\u0027t is when it\u0027s initialized from an array of chars which is not a string, and it references the whole array. I don\u0027t see any use case for it, so let\u0027s ban that. All other cases - StringView(\"asdf\"), StringView(std::string), StringView(const char*) - have a valid *end().",
      "parentUuid": "9c7dca55_22a7ae5a",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 47,
        "startChar": 4,
        "endLine": 47,
        "endChar": 51
      },
      "revId": "39856ce8646c65ac26e12030542d35508ac972cd",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "dff9f4d6_f0c2defd",
        "filename": "android/base/network/IpAddress.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 52,
      "author": {
        "id": 1087048
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-10-10T18:05:45Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "In some places you use \"this-\u003e\" to access members and in other places you don\u0027t. Does our style guide mention any of this? I prefer not to have it, at least if members are prefix with \"m\", in this case I\u0027m fine with either. Would be nice if it was consistent though.",
      "revId": "39856ce8646c65ac26e12030542d35508ac972cd",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9c7dca55_62a1b642",
        "filename": "android/base/network/IpAddress.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 1
      },
      "lineNbr": 52,
      "author": {
        "id": 1000411
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-10-14T14:17:27Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I can see how this is annoying. This comes from the fact that the fields of a struct don\u0027t have the member-specific m prefix (see https://google.github.io/styleguide/cppguide.html#Variable_Names), because IpAddress started as a passive struct initially. This is no longer the case.\n\nWhen this happens, using |this-\u003efield| is used to make it explicit that the code is referencing the member, instead of a local variable. The |this-\u003e| prefix can be omitted if the context of the code is small / clear enough though.\n\nI\u0027d rather change it to a full class with accessors instead then, so we\u0027ll get consistent with the coding style.",
      "parentUuid": "dff9f4d6_f0c2defd",
      "revId": "39856ce8646c65ac26e12030542d35508ac972cd",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
